ing reflects the southwestern English dialect pronunciation.","History: This surname was brought to North America by Alexander Alvord, who came from Devon or Somerset to Windsor, CT, <i>c.</i> 1645. He had many prominent descendants."]},{"name":"Halford","meanings":["English (mainly Midlands): habitational name from any of various places called Halford. Most, for example those in Warwickshire, Devon, and Shropshire, or the lost place <i>Haleford</i> in Pembury (Kent), are named from Old English <i>halh</i> ‘nook, recess’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’.","English: variant of   Alford   with prosthetic <i>H-</i>."]},{"name":"Allford","meanings":["English: variant of   Alford  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":25,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John Alford was born in 1430, in Whitestaunton, Somerset, England, his father, Thomas Grantham Alford, was 25 and his mother, Frances Powell, was 20. He had at least 2 sons with Lady Elizabeth Brinks Oglethorpe. He died in 1487, in Whitestaunton, Somerset, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 57."},"et":{"1430–1487":"1430–1487","1430–1512":"1430–1512","1455–